{"version":3,"kind":"Article","sha256":"9fab6c9ade20b00500e6834b5d88ff684d772300fb7a6bee3d430de465d703b5","slug":"ribosome-profiling","location":"/metaproteomics/Ribosome_profiling.md","dependencies":[],"frontmatter":{"title":"Ribosome profiling","content_includes_title":false,"authors":[{"nameParsed":{"literal":"META-Insight Team","given":"META-Insight","family":"Team"},"name":"META-Insight Team","id":"contributors-myst-generated-uid-0"}],"github":"https://github.com/aababc1/metainsight-book","keywords":["metagenomics","metatranscriptomics","metaproteomics","microbiome","bioinformatics"],"numbering":{"title":{"offset":1}},"source_url":"https://github.com/aababc1/metainsight-book/blob/main/metaproteomics/Ribosome_profiling.md","edit_url":"https://github.com/aababc1/metainsight-book/edit/main/metaproteomics/Ribosome_profiling.md","thumbnail":"/metainsight-book/build/0d56656caea2762d4799b84a70e87207.png","exports":[{"format":"md","filename":"Ribosome_profiling.md","url":"/metainsight-book/build/Ribosome_profiling-06209b84fb2a59830463028536ee00ae.md"}]},"mdast":{"type":"root","children":[{"type":"block","children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"You can obtain results using ","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"p3Lbm9ImfT"},{"type":"link","url":"https://github.com/bhattlab/bhattlab_workflows/tree/master/metariboseq","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"plotVisualRibo.R","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"XQlP20Thxz"}],"urlSource":"https://github.com/bhattlab/bhattlab_workflows/tree/master/metariboseq","error":true,"key":"y0tnSXCw1R"},{"type":"text","value":" script that utilizes .bam files and results obtained from metagenomic analysis as input files. (Linux environment is recommended)","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"kzAD1xfssZ"}],"key":"qgVIDb5KvK"},{"type":"code","lang":"r","value":"#install RiboseqR\nif (!requireNamespace(\"BiocManager\", quietly = TRUE))\n    install.packages(\"BiocManager\")\nBiocManager::install(\"RiboseqR\")","position":{"start":{"line":5,"column":1},"end":{"line":10,"column":1}},"key":"jVQYfjBarl"},{"type":"code","lang":"bash","value":"#ribo-seq running\n#file download in https://github.com/bhattlab/bhattlab_workflows/tree/master/metariboseq\n$ Rscript plotVisualRibo.R final.contigs.fa sample_metariboseq.bam","position":{"start":{"line":11,"column":1},"end":{"line":15,"column":1}},"key":"qal6AxQRR6"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":17,"column":1},"end":{"line":17,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"In summary, five types of files are generated as a result: “allFSshift.pdf,” “histogram.pdf,” and “plotCDSfilt.pdf” (with three variations for different footprints, i.e., 28, 31, and 35).","position":{"start":{"line":17,"column":1},"end":{"line":17,"column":1}},"key":"Z0oovwelfp"}],"key":"OpHSshqZpA"},{"type":"container","children":[{"type":"image","style":{"width":"90%"},"url":"/metainsight-book/build/0d56656caea2762d4799b84a70e87207.png","alt":"Example of the allFSshift.pdf file generated by the plotVisualRibo.R results","data":{"altTextIsAutoGenerated":true},"key":"wQGlqAlyU6","urlSource":"https://github.com/sujin9819/MetaInsight/blob/main/SOP/MetaProteomic/img/P_7_1.png?raw=true"},{"type":"caption","children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"strong","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Example of the allFSshift.pdf file generated by the plotVisualRibo.R results","key":"tOwqytB0bJ"}],"key":"KYe7sF3QNz"}],"key":"CPx1zM9sSr"}],"key":"Sh7n0y1fhf"}],"enumerator":"1","key":"p1Njq7vuZl"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":24,"column":1},"end":{"line":27,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Regarding the “allFSshift.pdf” results, this file provides frame information and the proportion of each frame for codon periodicity.\nIn the image above (an example from “allFSshift.pdf”), the x-axis represents the footprint (size), and the y-axis represents the number of reads.\nThis information is used as an indicator to predict the periodicity of gene nucleotide sequences in codons. It helps determine how ribosome-bound mRNA footprints are captured based on whether they align with a specific reading frame.\nIt’s important to note that the results of this periodicity may exhibit different patterns among microbial species, reflecting variations in their translation mechanisms.","position":{"start":{"line":24,"column":1},"end":{"line":24,"column":1}},"key":"Ychr0xR9oy"}],"key":"sQOd9ldYF7"},{"type":"container","children":[{"type":"image","style":{"width":"90%"},"url":"/metainsight-book/build/14da0a26660b4be3c0a8ed3f3068c13a.png","alt":"Example of the histogram.pdf(left) and plotCDSfilt.pdf(right) file generated by the plotVisualRibo.R results","data":{"altTextIsAutoGenerated":true},"key":"n18lVmfoC6","urlSource":"https://github.com/sujin9819/MetaInsight/blob/main/SOP/MetaProteomic/img/P_7_2.png?raw=true"},{"type":"caption","children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"strong","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Example of the histogram.pdf(left) and plotCDSfilt.pdf(right) file generated by the plotVisualRibo.R results","key":"uUYfCo2RFx"}],"key":"xG2KOfY3nz"}],"key":"Lk3ZRPDfnH"}],"key":"FoUPx6zLSG"}],"enumerator":"2","key":"kF8WNjTnDK"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":34,"column":1},"end":{"line":38,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"The Histogram.pdf results in a graph that shows the length of reads and the alignment rate, allowing you to determine if there are a significant number of reads of specific lengths and the proportion of those reads in the dataset.\nThe plotCDSfilt.pdf files are generated for ribosome footprint sizes of 28, 31, and 35, resulting in three PDF files.\nIn contrast to RNA-seq results, ribo-seq results exhibit strong signals at the start codon and stop codon. This phenomenon is related to the characteristics of ribosomes during mRNA translation.\nRibosomes spend a longer time recognizing mRNA and preparing for translation during the start codon recognition phase, and the same happens at the stop codon when translation terminates.\nThis leads to the strong signals observed at the start and stop codons.","position":{"start":{"line":34,"column":1},"end":{"line":34,"column":1}},"key":"uh5Z74AGa6"}],"key":"XYVNUCz2eb"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":40,"column":1},"end":{"line":42,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"By using this information, you can obtain the count values for ribosome-bound mRNA. These count values provide information about the location of ribosomes and their proportions during translation.\nUtilizing this ribosome information, you can indirectly gather insights related to protein synthesis.\nHowever, analyzing ribosome-bound mRNA information alongside transcriptome data often yields more comprehensive and insightful results.","position":{"start":{"line":40,"column":1},"end":{"line":40,"column":1}},"key":"SnVX52fWrM"}],"key":"dI3VImLzSy"},{"type":"container","children":[{"type":"image","style":{"width":"90%"},"url":"/metainsight-book/build/undefined","alt":"Predicted translation efficiency; [ref]","data":{"altTextIsAutoGenerated":true},"key":"ID18Z9rG30","urlSource":"https://github.com/sujin9819/MetaInsight/blob/main/SOP/MetaProteomic/img/P_7_3.png?raw=true"},{"type":"caption","children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"strong","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Predicted translation efficiency; ","key":"keam4nc2bO"},{"type":"cite","url":"https://doi.org/10.1038/nrm4069","children":[{"type":"text","value":"[ref]","key":"GdJKF9mmmr"}],"kind":"narrative","label":"Brar_2015","identifier":"https://doi.org/10.1038/nrm4069","enumerator":"1","key":"tEUojSFPPh"}],"key":"TO1fnQ7Y25"}],"key":"